                  <handDesc><!--ACHTUNG! first HandNote comes from writing system in Ethiospare. the others are one for each CHANGE OF HAND-->
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <ab type="script">Hand a: mediocre; hand b: fine, regular.</ab>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid red: hand a; strong red: hand b)</seg>
                        <persName role="scribe" corresp="PRS00000">Wäldä Śǝllase (?), Gäbrä Ḥǝywät</persName>The text of quire I might have been written by Wäldä Śǝllase (hand a). He is mentioned as scribe and comissioner in the supplication note of Text I-1 (fol. 8vb, the note is somewhat unclear). &#xD;
Gäbrä Ḥǝywät (hand b) is mentioned as the scribe on fols. 20rb, 35ra, for the text in quires II-XIV.<date>Late 19th or first half of the 20th century</date>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">Hand a, Wäldä Śǝllase (?): quire I (Text I-1). The script is characterized by small letters with short hairlines. Many letters have forked hook vowel markers (e.g., ብ, ን, ገ).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
Hand b, Gäbrä Ḥǝywät: quires II-XIV (Texts I-2 until I-13). The handwriting is regular throughout the Ms. (except at the very end, s. fol. 101r) with rounded, upright letters.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
